            "body": "> Sorry, these are enabled by default for a reason. You can always put `vim.treesitter.stop()` in an autocommand or ftplugin in your config.\n\nThis issue cannot be resolved solely by using an ftplugin file.\n\nWe need a variable to prevent execut of `vim.treesitter.start()`.\n\nThis is analogous to `did_ftplugin` which, when set to true or 1, prevents subsequent executions of the ftplugin during a runtime session.\n\nFurthermore, using autocmds cannot entirely mitigate the introduced latency.\n\nConsider this example:\n* **A file located at `runtime/ftplugin/lua.lua`:**\n  ```lua\n  vim.treesitter.start();\n  vim.print(\"run!\");\n  ```\n* **A file located at `.config/nvim/init.lua`:**\n  ```lua\n  vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"FileType\", {\n    pattern = \"lua\",\n    callback = function()\n      vim.treesitter.stop();\n      vim.print(\"stop!\");\n    end\n  })\n  ```\n\nUpon opening a Lua file, the following log is observed:\n```\nrun!\nstop!\nPress ENTER or type command to continue\n```\nAs you can see, Tree-sitter initializes fully and then terminates.\nIf the Lua file is large, this execution, coupled with the delay, persists until the Tree-sitter operation completes and subsequently halts.\n\nThis demonstrates that while the autocmd attempts to stop Tree-sitter, it does so after the initial startup, leading to unnecessary delays, especially for larger files.\n",
